  "text_preview": "\"number\" ASL American Sign Language ASL University ► numbers 100-900 Note: Don't get hung up on making perfect \"C\" handshapes. I'm not doing the \"flying pinkie\" on purpose in some of the following signs. It is just a straggler. But I'm not concerned about it either. It's a non-issue. When you practice, go ahead and use a \"good looking\" C handshape, but realize that later on as you become fluent the shape will \"morph\" a bit. To sign numbers 101 through 109 I just show 1-0-1, 1-0-2, 1-0-3...1-0-9. Meaning, I show the individual number \"one,\" quickly followed by a \"zero,\" and another \"one\" to show the number 101. Some people sign: 1C1 to mean 101. Or they use a modified \"index-finger-C\" (see below) followed by a 1. I prefer the \"zero\" method. The rest of the \"hundred\" series (111, through 199"
}
